<section class="faq" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
  <div class="section-head">
    <span class="section-eyebrow" id="faq-heading">◆ COMMON QUESTIONS</span>
    <span class="section-rule"></span>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2 class="faq-q">Can Shopify automatically cancel unpaid orders?</h2>
      <p class="faq-a">No. Shopify has no native setting that cancels an unpaid or pending order after a set time. Cancelling an order is a manual action you take one order at a time from the admin, and even Shopify Flow, the free automation tool, cannot cancel an order at all. So orders placed with manual payment methods like bank transfer, cash on delivery, or an unpaid invoice, plus stale draft orders, sit in pending payment until someone notices them and clears them by hand. Auto-cancellation only exists if you install a third-party app or build it yourself.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2 class="faq-q">Do unpaid orders hold inventory on Shopify?</h2>
      <p class="faq-a">Yes. When an order is placed, Shopify commits the inventory to it, and that stock stays committed while the order sits in pending payment. A pending bank transfer or an unpaid cash-on-delivery order can therefore hold units off the shelf for days, which is how a store shows sold out while real, paying customers are turned away. The committed stock is only released when the order is cancelled with the restock option, which on a plain store is a manual click per order, so the inventory leaks quietly until a human gets to it.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2 class="faq-q">How long should you wait before cancelling an unpaid order?</h2>
      <p class="faq-a">It depends on the payment method and the customer, which is exactly why one global timer is wrong. A bank transfer that clears in two business days needs a different window than a cash-on-delivery order or a wholesale invoice with agreed terms. The sound approach is to nudge the customer once or twice with a clear way to pay, give a window that fits how that payment method actually settles, then cancel and restock only the orders that stay cold, while leaving alone the one that just paid an hour late. A flat rule that cancels everything at forty-eight hours will cancel orders that were about to pay.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

